omedy’s Burlesque of History -- tPart V: Loci and Tempora -- tThe Myth of Opheltes at Nemea in the Context of Rivalry in the Archaic Peloponnese -- tMarginal Remarks on the Concept of ‘Time of Origins’ in Classical Greek Culture -- tMyth and History in the Court of Archelaus -- tPart VI: Roman Era and Late Antiquity -- t“Oceans Rise, Empires Fall”: Cyclical Time and History in Seneca’s Quaestiones Naturales 3 -- tHerodotus’ Phoenix between Hesiod and Papyrus Harris 500, and Its Legacy in Tacitus -- tEmpire, Ethnicity, Exegesis: Lucian on Interpretations of Greek Myth in the Roman Mediterranean -- tMyth and History in Libanius’ Imperial Speeches -- tMyth and Levels of Language in the Octavia -- tAppendix -- tThe Editors -- tThe Contributors -- tIndex Rerum et Nominum Notabiliorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fluidity of myth and history in antiquity and the ensuing rapidity with which these notions infiltrated and cross-fertilized one another has repeatedly attracted the scholarly interest. The understanding of myth as a phenomenon imbued with social and historical nuances allows for more than one methodological approaches. Within the wider context of interdisciplinary exchange of ideas, the present volume returns to origins, as it traces and registers the association and interaction between myth and history in various literary genres in Greek and Roman antiquity (i.e. an era when the scientific definitions of and distinctions between myth and history had not yet been perceived as such, let alone fully shaped and implemented), providing original ideas, new interpretations and (re)evaluations of key texts and less well-known passages, close readings, and catholic overviews. The twenty-four chapters of this volume expand from Greek epos to lyric poetry, historiography, dramatic poetry and even beyond, to genres of Roman era and late antiquity. It is the editors’ hope that this volume will appeal to students and academic researchers in the areas of classics, social and political history, archaeology, and even social anthropology.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMythology, Greek. 0aMythology, Roman. 4aGeschichte. 4aMythos.  ahistory.  amyth.1 aAllen, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntonopoulos, Andreas P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntonopoulos, Andreas P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntypas, Constantine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBershadsky, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBravo, Jorge J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgess, Jonathan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristopoulos, Menelaos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristopoulos, Menelaos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCipolla, Paolo B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Serio, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, George W. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarakantza, Efimia D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarla, Grammatiki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKousoulini, Vasiliki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLecocq, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevaniouk, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLytle, Ephraim, econtributor.4ctb4